/* <orly/lang_tests/general/variants_set_storage.orly>

   End-to-end test for storing a SET of variants (issue #96).

   A single variant value round-trips through storage (see
   variants_storage.orly). A SET of variants was the deeper case: a sabot
   set requires a homogeneous element type, but the original #95 encoding
   stored each variant as its active arm's single-key record
   (`<{.Integer: int}>` vs `<{.Deleted: <{}>}>`) -- differently-shaped, so
   a set of differently-tagged variants was heterogeneous on disk and the
   write-path conversion (Var::ToVar over the serialized set) tripped the
   homogeneity check in orly/var/set.cc.

   Issue #96 fixed this by re-encoding every value of one declared variant
   as the SAME fixed-shape record

     <| Integer(int) | Deleted |>.Integer(1)
        -> <{ .$which: 1, .Deleted: <empty-opt>, .Integer: 1? }>

   -- a `$which` discriminant (un-expressible in orlyscript, so it never
   collides with a user field) plus one optional payload field per arm,
   only the active arm's optional set. Every value of the variant then
   shares one record type, so a set of differently-tagged variants is
   homogeneous; the `$which` sentinel lets the read path reconstruct a
   variant (value and type) without the call-site `::(T)` crutch. See
   orly/var/new_sabot.h, orly/type/new_sabot.cc, orly/var/sabot_to_var.cc,
   and orly/type/sabot_to_type.cc.

   Copyright 2010-2026 Atomic Kismet Company

   Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");
   you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.
   You may obtain a copy of the License at

     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0

   Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software
   distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,
   WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.
   See the License for the specific language governing permissions and
   limitations under the License. */

read_var_set = (*<[n]>::({<| Integer(int) | Deleted |>})) where {
  n = given::(int);
};

with {
  <[402]> <- {
    <| Integer(int) | Deleted |>.Integer(1),
    <| Integer(int) | Deleted |>.Integer(2),
    <| Integer(int) | Deleted |>.Deleted
  };
} test {
  t1: read_var_set(.n: 402) == {
    <| Integer(int) | Deleted |>.Integer(1),
    <| Integer(int) | Deleted |>.Integer(2),
    <| Integer(int) | Deleted |>.Deleted
  };
};
